=========================================
GENERIC LAMBDA (C++14)
=========================================
5 Points to Remember
--------------------

1. Introduced in C++14.
2. Uses `auto` for lambda parameters.
3. Works with any data type.
4. Implemented internally as a templated `operator()`.
5. Widely used with STL algorithms.


What is a Generic Lambda?
-------------------------
• Introduced in C++14.
• A lambda whose parameters are declared using `auto`.
• The compiler automatically deduces the parameter types.
• Makes lambdas generic, similar to function templates.

--------------------------------------------------

Before C++14
------------

auto add = [](int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
};

Works only for int.

--------------------------------------------------

C++14 Generic Lambda
--------------------

auto add = [](auto a, auto b)
{
    return a + b;
};

add(10, 20);                  // int
add(3.5, 2.5);                // double
add(string("Hi "), string("C++"));   // string

One lambda works with multiple data types.

--------------------------------------------------

How does the Compiler Implement It?***********************
-----------------------------------

A generic lambda is conceptually equivalent to:

class Lambda
{
public:

    template<typename T1, typename T2>
    auto operator()(T1 a, T2 b) const
    {
        return a + b;
    }
};

Lambda add;

Interview Point:
A generic lambda is syntactic sugar for a closure class with a templated
`operator()`.

--------------------------------------------------

Why was it introduced?
----------------------

Before C++14:

template<typename T>
T square(T x)
{
    return x * x;
}

C++14:

auto square = [](auto x)
{
    return x * x;
};

Less code, easier generic programming.

--------------------------------------------------

Generic Lambda with Different Types
-----------------------------------

auto print = [](auto a, auto b)
{
    cout << a << " " << b;
};

print(10, "Hello");
print(3.14, 'A');

Each parameter type is deduced independently.

--------------------------------------------------

Generic Lambda with Capture
---------------------------

int x = 10;

auto f = [x](auto y)
{
    return x + y;
};

cout << f(20);
cout << f(5.5);

Captures work exactly like normal lambdas.

--------------------------------------------------

Generic Lambda with STL
-----------------------

vector<int> v{5,2,8,1};

sort(v.begin(), v.end(),
[](auto a, auto b)
{
    return a < b;
});

Commonly used with STL algorithms.

--------------------------------------------------

Advantages
----------

✔ Less boilerplate
✔ Works with any data type
✔ Cleaner generic programming
✔ No need to write function templates
✔ Commonly used with STL algorithms

--------------------------------------------------

Normal Lambda vs Generic Lambda  *******************
-------------------------------

Normal Lambda

[](int x)
{
    return x * x;
}

• Fixed parameter type
• Works only for int

--------------------------------------------------

Generic Lambda

[](auto x)
{
    return x * x;
}

• Parameter type deduced automatically
• Works for int, double, string, etc.

--------------------------------------------------

Most Asked Interview Questions
------------------------------

Q. What is a Generic Lambda?
A. A lambda whose parameters are declared using `auto`, allowing the compiler to deduce the parameter types.

--------------------------------------------------

Q. Which C++ version introduced Generic Lambdas?
A. C++14.

--------------------------------------------------

Q. How is a Generic Lambda implemented internally?*******
A. A generic lambda is internally converted by the compiler into a unique closure
(class) that has a templated `operator()`. Each time you call the lambda with
different argument types, the compiler instantiates the appropriate version of
`operator()`, just like a function template.

auto add = [](auto a, auto b)
{
    return a + b;
};

The compiler conceptually generates something like:
class Lambda
{
public:
    template<typename T1, typename T2>
    auto operator()(T1 a, T2 b) const
    {
        return a + b;
    }
};

When you call:add(10, 20);
The compiler generates:operator()<int, int>(10, 20);

A generic lambda is essentially syntactic sugar for a compiler-generated closure class whose operator() is a 
function template. Each call instantiates the appropriate version based on the argument types.

--------------------------------------------------

Q. Difference between a normal lambda and a generic lambda?
A.
• Normal lambda has fixed parameter types.
• Generic lambda uses `auto` and works with multiple types.

--------------------------------------------------

Q. Is a Generic Lambda the same as a function template?
A. Conceptually yes. Internally, it is implemented using a templated `operator()` inside the closure class.

--------------------------------------------------

Q. Can Generic Lambdas capture variables?
A. Yes. They support all lambda capture modes (`[]`, `[=]`, `[&]`, init-capture) just like normal lambdas.

--------------------------------------------------

